  "prompt": "How do you determine the Lewis structure of SO2?",
  "response": "To determine the Lewis structure of SO2 (sulfur dioxide), follow these steps:\n\n1. Count the total number of valence electrons:\n- Sulfur (S): 6 valence electrons\n- Oxygen (O): 6 valence electrons \u00d7 2 = 12\n- Total valence electrons: 6 + 12 = 18\n\n2. Arrange atoms:\n- Put sulfur in the center\n- Place oxygen atoms on either side\n\n3. Connect atoms with single bonds:\n- Draw a single bond between sulfur and each oxygen\n\n4. Distribute remaining electrons as lone pairs:\n- Complete octets for oxygen atoms first\n- Place remaining electrons around sulfur\n\n5. Check formal charges to ensure the most stable structure:\n- Adjust electron placement if necessary\n\nThe final Lewis structure of SO2 will have:\n- Central sulfur atom\n- Double bonds to each oxygen\n- Lone pairs on oxygen atoms\n- One lone pair on sulfur\n- Total of 18 electrons distributed\n\nThe structure shows resonance between two equivalent forms with double bonds in different positions.\n\nWould you like me to elaborate on any of these steps?",
